The space segment for GEO missile warning satellites consists of a resilient architecture providing real time persistent global
equatorial infrared coverage. The first GEO satellite is required in 2026.

FY 2026 Plans:
FY 2026 funds are required to execute launch & on-orbit testing and interim contractor operations support for Space Vehicle
(SV)#1, preserve 2027 initial launch capability (ILC) for SV#2, perform space/ground integration activities, and continue build and
integration activities for SV#2. Continue executing ground system mission data processing, command and control, and integration
development to support SV#1 and SV#2. Conduct system level assembly and test for SV#2, including space-to-ground testing
to enable discovery and correction of defects critical to launch. Conduct SV#2 space vehicle baseline test, electromagnetic
interference test and acoustic test. Rapidly respond to implement system resiliency and situational awareness necessary to
operate in the contested space domain. Activities may include, but are not limited to, program office support, studies, technical
analysis, experimentation, risk reduction, prototyping, and activities that may leverage commercial, U.S. Government partnership,
and international opportunities to respond to existing and emerging adversarial threats with speed and agility.
FY 2027 Plans:
FY 2027 funds are required to ensure the successful transition of Space Vehicle (SV)#1 to operational status and preserves the
2027 Initial Launch Capability for SV#2. This includes completing on-orbit testing of SV#1 and maintaining interim contractor
operations support throughout the operational acceptance phase; supporting the necessary space-to-ground integration activities;
continuation of build and integration efforts for SV#2, encompassing vital processes such as completion of environmental
Thermal-Vacuum testing, Acoustic testing and Space Vehicle Final test. Continue integrating the ground system's mission data
processing, command and control, and overall integration to support SV#2's operations and the program's ultimate transition
to Future Operationally Resilient Ground Evolution (FORGE). Rapidly respond to implement system resiliency and situational
awareness necessary to operate in the contested space domain. Activities may include, but are not limited to, program office
support, studies, technical analysis, experimentation, risk reduction, prototyping, and activities that may leverage commercial, U.S.
Government partnership, and international opportunities to respond to existing and emerging adversarial threats with speed and
agility.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
FY 2027 increased by $63.530 million from FY 2026 due to SV#2 environmental Thermal-Vacuum testing, Acoustic testing, Space
Vehicle Final testing, and final integration testing. Funds are required to ensure SV#2 meets its 2027 launch date.
